        </p>

        <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold text-ink">Why 529 Plans Are Usually Better for College Savings</h3>

        <p class="mb-4">
          The <strong>compounding tax advantage</strong> of a 529 plan is substantial over a typical 13-year savings horizon (age 5 to 18). Consider a real-world example: saving <strong>$10,000 initially plus $500/month</strong> for 13 years at a <strong>7% annual return</strong> with a <strong>2% dividend yield</strong> and a <strong>24% parent tax bracket</strong>:
        </p>

        <ul class="mb-4 space-y-2">
          <li><strong>529 Plan:</strong> No annual tax on dividends or capital gains. The full balance grows tax-free. At age 18, the projected balance is approximately <strong>$161,000</strong> — every dollar available for education.</li>
          <li><strong>UTMA Account:</strong> Subject to Kiddie Tax each year. The first $1,350 of dividends is tax-free, the next $1,350 is taxed at 10%, and everything above is taxed at 24%. Over 13 years, the Kiddie Tax drag reduces the balance by approximately <strong>$8,000–$12,000</strong>, leaving roughly <strong>$149,000–$153,000</strong>.</li>
          <li><strong>Total 529 advantage:</strong> <strong>$8,000–$12,000 more</strong> in the 529 plan — and that is before accounting for the FAFSA advantage!</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold text-ink">Key Features of This 529 vs UTMA Calculator</h3>

        <p class="mb-4">
          This calculator provides <strong>instant side-by-side projections</strong> as you adjust any input. Enter your initial contribution, monthly contribution, expected annual return, dividend yield, your marginal tax rate, your child&#39;s age, and the number of years until college. The calculator applies the 2026 Kiddie Tax brackets automatically, showing you the exact annual tax drag on the UTMA account. The interactive <strong>growth comparison chart</strong> plots both accounts year by year, making the compounding advantage of tax-free growth immediately visible. Key result cards highlight the projected balance at college age, the total tax paid, and the net advantage of choosing a 529 plan.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-4">
